 10  /-!
 11    # ring_exp tactic
 12  
 13    A tactic for solving equations in commutative (semi)rings,
 14    where the exponents can also contain variables.
 15  
 16    More precisely, expressions of the following form are supported:
 17    - constants (non-negative integers)
 18    - variables
 19    - coefficients (any rational number, embedded into the (semi)ring)
 20    - addition of expressions
 21    - multiplication of expressions
 22    - exponentiation of expressions (the exponent must have type `ℕ`)
 23    - subtraction and negation of expressions (if the base is a full ring)
 24  
 25    The motivating example is proving `2 * 2^n * b = b * 2^(n+1)`,
 26    something that the `ring` tactic cannot do, but `ring_exp` can.
 27  
 28    ## Implementation notes
 29  
 30    The basic approach to prove equalities is to normalise both sides and check for equality.
 31    The normalisation is guided by building a value in the type `ex` at the meta level,
 32    together with a proof (at the base level) that the original value is equal to
 33    the normalised version.
 34    The normalised version and normalisation proofs are also stored in the `ex` type.
 35  
 36    The outline of the file:
 37    - Define an inductive family of types `ex`, parametrised over `ex_type`,
 38      which can represent expressions with `+`, `*`, `^` and rational numerals.
st     ┴
 39      The parametrisation over `ex_type` ensures that associativity and distributivity are applied,
 40      by restricting which kinds of subexpressions appear as arguments to the various operators.
 41    - Represent addition, multiplication and exponentiation in the `ex` type,
 42      thus allowing us to map expressions to `ex` (the `eval` function drives this).
 43      We apply associativity and distributivity of the operators here (helped by `ex_type`)
 44      and commutativity as well (by sorting the subterms; unfortunately not helped by anything).
 45      Any expression not of the above formats is treated as an atom (the same as a variable).
 46  
 47    There are some details we glossed over which make the plan more complicated:
 48    - The order on atoms is not initially obvious.
 49      We construct a list containing them in order of initial appearance in the expression,
 50      then use the index into the list as a key to order on.
 51    - In the tactic, a normalized expression `ps : ex` lives in the meta-world,
 52      but the normalization proofs live in the real world.
 53      Thus, we cannot directly say `ps.orig = ps.pretty` anywhere,
 54      but we have to carefully construct the proof when we compute `ps`.
 55      This was a major source of bugs in development!
 56    - For `pow`, the exponent must be a natural number, while the base can be any semiring `α`.
 57      We swap out operations for the base ring `α` with those for the exponent ring `ℕ`
 58      as soon as we deal with exponents.
 59      This is accomplished by the `in_exponent` function and is relatively painless since
 60      we work in a `reader` monad.
 61    - The normalized form of an expression is the one that is useful for the tactic,
 62      but not as nice to read. To remedy this, the user-facing normalization calls `ex.simp`.
 63  
 64    ## Caveats and future work
 65  
 66    Subtraction cancels out identical terms, but division does not.
 67    That is: `a - a = 0 := by ring_exp` solves the goal,
 68    but `a / a := 1 by ring_exp` doesn't.
 69    Note that `0 / 0` is generally defined to be `0`,
 70    so division cancelling out is not true in general.
 71  
 72    Multiplication of powers can be simplified a little bit further:
 73    `2 ^ n * 2 ^ n = 4 ^ n := by ring_exp` could be implemented
 74    in a similar way that `2 * a + 2 * a = 4 * a := by ring_exp` already works.
st         ┴
 75    This feature wasn't needed yet, so it's not implemented yet.
 76  
 77    ## Tags
 78  
 79    ring, semiring, exponent, power

 90  /--
 91    The `atom` structure is used to represent atomic expressions:
 92    those which `ring_exp` cannot parse any further.
 93  
 94    For instance, `a + (a % b)` has `a` and `(a % b)` as atoms.
 95    The `ring_exp_eq` tactic does not normalize the subexpressions in atoms,
 96    but `ring_exp` does if `ring_exp_eq` was not sufficient.
 97  
 98    Atoms in fact represent equivalence classes of expressions,
 99    modulo definitional equality.
100    The field `index : ℕ` should be a unique number for each class,
101    while `value : expr` contains a representative of this class.
102    The function `resolve_atom` determines the appropriate atom
103    for a given expression.
104  -/
105  meta structure atom : Type := (value : expr) (index : ℕ)
id                                          └──┘           ┴
src                                         └──┘           ┴
typ                                         └──┘           ┴
doc                                         └──┘
106  namespace atom
107  /--
108    The `eq` operation on `atom`s works modulo definitional equality,
109    ignoring their `value`s.
110    The invariants on `atom` ensure indices are unique per value.
111    Thus, `eq` indicates equality as long as the `atom`s come from the same context.
112  -/
113  meta def eq (a b : atom) : bool := a.index = b.index

152  /--
153    Each `ex` stores information for its normalization proof.
154  
155    The `orig` expression is the expression that was passed to `eval`.
156  
157    The `pretty` expression is the normalised form that the `ex` represents.
158    (I didn't call this something like `norm`, because there are already
159    too many things called `norm` in mathematics!)
160  
161    The field `proof` contains an optional proof term of type `%%orig = %%pretty`.
162    The value `none` for the proof indicates that everything reduces to reflexivity.
163    (Which saves space in quite a lot of cases.)
164  -/
165  meta structure ex_info : Type :=
166  (orig : expr) (pretty : expr) (proof : option expr)
id           └──┘            └──┘           └────┘ └──┘
src          └──┘            └──┘           └────┘ └──┘
typ          └──┘            └──┘           └────┘ └──┘
doc          └──┘            └──┘                  └──┘
167  
168  /--
169    The `ex` type is an abstract representation of an expression with `+`, `*` and `^`.
170    Those operators are mapped to the `sum`, `prod` and `exp` constructors respectively.
171  
172    The `zero` constructor is the base case for `ex sum`, e.g. `1 + 2` is represented
173    by (something along the lines of) `sum 1 (sum 2 zero)`.
174  
175    The `coeff` constructor is the base case for `ex prod`, and is used for numerals.
176    The code maintains the invariant that the coefficient is never `0`.
177  
178    The `var` constructor is the base case for `ex exp`, and is used for atoms.
179  
180    The `sum_b` constructor allows for addition in the base of an exponentiation;
181    it serves a similar purpose as the parentheses in `(a + b)^c`.
182    The code maintains the invariant that the argument to `sum_b` is not `zero`
183    or `sum _ zero`.
184  
185    All of the constructors contain an `ex_info` field,
186    used to carry around (arguments to) proof terms.
187  
188    While the `ex_type` parameter enforces some simplification invariants,
189    the following ones must be manually maintained at the risk of insufficient power:
190     - the argument to `coeff` must be nonzero (to ensure `0 = 0 * 1`)
191     - the argument to `sum_b` must be of the form `sum a (sum b bs)` (to ensure `(a + 0)^n = a^n`)
192     - normalisation proofs of subexpressions must be `refl ps.pretty`
193     - if we replace `sum` with `cons` and `zero` with `nil`, the resulting list is sorted
194       according to the `lt` relation defined further down; similarly for `prod` and `coeff`
195       (to ensure `a + b = b + a`).
196  
197    The first two invariants could be encoded in a subtype of `ex`,
198    but aren't (yet) to spare some implementation burden.
199    The other invariants cannot be encoded because we need the `tactic` monad to check them.
200    (For example, the correct equality check of `expr` is `is_def_eq : expr → expr → tactic unit`.)
201  -/

321  section operations
322  /-!
323    ### `operations` section
324    This section defines the operations (on `ex`) that use tactics.
325    They live in the `ring_exp_m` monad,
326    which adds a cache and a list of encountered atoms to the `tactic` monad.
327  
328    Throughout this section, we will be constructing proof terms.
329    The lemmas used in the construction are all defined over a commutative semiring α.
330  -/
331  variables {α : Type u} [comm_semiring α]
id                           └───────────┘
src                          └───────────┘

333  open tactic
334  open ex_type
335  
336  /--
337    Stores the information needed in the `eval` function and its dependencies,
338    so they can (re)construct expressions.
339  
340    The `eval_info` structure stores this information for one type,
341    and the `context` combines the two types, one for bases and one for exponents.
342  -/
343  meta structure eval_info :=
344    (α : expr) (univ : level)

typ                    └──┘                 └──┘                 └──┘                 └──┘
doc                    └──┘                 └──┘                 └──┘                 └──┘

352  /--

654  /--
655    Represents the way in which two products are equal except coefficient.
656  
657    This type is used in the function `add_overlap`.
658    In order to deal with equations of the form `a * 2 + a = 3 * a`,
659    the `add` function will add up overlapping products,
660    turning `a * 2 + a` into `a * 3`.
661    We need to distinguish `a * 2 + a` from `a * 2 + b` in order to do this,
662    and the `overlap` type carries the information on how it overlaps.
663  
664    The case `none` corresponds to non-overlapping products, e.g. `a * 2 + b`;
665    the case `nonzero` to overlapping products adding to non-zero, e.g. `a * 2 + a`
666    (the `ex prod` field will then look like `a * 3` with a proof that `a * 2 + a = a * 3`);
667    the case `zero` to overlapping products adding to zero, e.g. `a * 2 + a * -2`.
668    We distinguish those two cases because in the second, the whole product reduces to `0`.
669  
670    A potential extension to the tactic would also do this for the base of exponents,
671    e.g. to show `2^n * 2^n = 4^n`.
672  -/
673  meta inductive overlap : Type
674  | none {} : overlap
675  | nonzero : ex prod → overlap
id               └┘ └──┘
src              └┘ └──┘
typ              └┘ └──┘
doc              └┘
676  | zero : ex sum → overlap
id            └┘ └─┘
src           └┘ └─┘
typ           └┘ └─┘
doc           └┘

751  /--
752    Add two expressions.
753  
754     * `0 + qs = 0`
755     * `ps + 0 = 0`
756     * `ps * x + ps * y = ps * (x + y)` (for `x`, `y` coefficients; uses `add_overlap`)

826  /--
827    Multiply two expressions.
828  
829    * `x * y = (x * y)` (for `x`, `y` coefficients)
830    * `x * (q * qs) = q * (qs * x)` (for `x` coefficient)
831    * `(p * ps) * y = p * (ps * y)` (for `y` coefficient)
832    * `(p_b^p_e * ps) * (p_b^q_e * qs) = p_b^(p_e + q_e) * (ps * qs)`
833        (if `p_e` and `q_e` are identical except coefficient)
834    * `(p * ps) * (q * qs) = p * (ps * (q * qs))` (if `p.lt q`)
835    * `(p * ps) * (q * qs) = q * ((p * ps) * qs)` (if not `p.lt q`)
836  -/

1183  /--
1184    Performs a lookup of the atom `a` in the list of known atoms,
1185    or allocates a new one.
1186  
1187    If `a` is not definitionally equal to any of the list's entries,
1188    a new atom is appended to the list and returned.
1189    The index of this atom is kept track of in the second inductive argument.
1190  
1191    This function is mostly useful in `resolve_atom`,
1192    which updates the state with the new list of atoms.
1193  -/
1194  meta def resolve_atom_aux (a : expr) : list atom → ℕ → ring_exp_m (atom × list atom)

1202  /--
1203    Convert the expression to an atom:
1204    either look up a definitionally equal atom,
1205    or allocate it as a new atom.

1211  meta def resolve_atom (a : expr) : ring_exp_m atom := do

1285    This section deals with going from `expr` to `ex` and back.
1286  
1287    The main attraction is `eval`, which uses `add`, `mul`, etc.
1288    to calculate an `ex` from a given `expr`.
